[src:capacity-planning/capacity-management] And because applications run over these networks, application performance suffers.
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-management] Various intelligent solutions are available to ensure that traffic over the network is effectively managed to optimize performance for all users.
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-management] Network performance management (NPM) consists of measuring, modeling, planning, and optimizing networks to ensure that they carry traffic with the speed, reliability, and capacity that is appropriate for the nature of the application and the cost constraints of the organization.
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-management] Different applications warrant different blends of capacity, latency, and reliability.
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-management] Network Performance management is a core component of the FCAPS ISO telecommunications framework (the 'P' stands for Performance in this acronym).
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-management] It enables the network engineers to proactively prepare for degradations in their IT infrastructure and ultimately help the end-user experience.
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-management] Network managers perform many tasks; these include performance measurement, forensic analysis, capacity planning, and load-testing or load generation.
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-management] They also work closely with application developers and IT departments who rely on them to deliver underlying network services.
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-management] Next-generation NPM tools are those that improve network management by automating the collection of network data, including capacity issues, and automatically interpreting it.
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-management] Terry Slattery, editor at NoJitter.com, compares three such tools, VMWare's vRealize Network Insight, PathSolutions TotalView, and Kemp Flowmon, in the article *The Future of Network Performance Management*, June 10, 2021.
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-management] New approaches to network management promise to help us detect and resolve network problems...
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-planning] The phrase is also used in business computing and information technology as a synonym for capacity management.
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-planning] IT capacity planning involves estimating the storage, computer hardware, software and connection infrastructure resources required over some future period of time.
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-planning] A common concern of enterprises is whether the required resources are in place to handle an increase in users or number of interactions.
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-planning] Capacity management is concerned about adding central processing units (CPUs), memory and storage to a physical or virtual server.
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-planning] This has been the traditional and vertical way of scaling up web applications, however IT capacity planning has been developed with the goal of forecasting the requirements for this vertical scaling approach.
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-planning] A discrepancy between the capacity of an organization and the demands of its customers results in inefficiency, either in under-utilized resources or unfulfilled customer demand.
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-planning] The goal of capacity planning is to minimize this discrepancy.
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-planning] Demand for an organization's capacity varies based on changes in production output, such as increasing or decreasing the production quantity of an existing product, or producing new products.
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-planning] Better utilization of existing capacity can be accomplished through improvements in overall equipment effectiveness (OEE).
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-planning] Capacity can be increased through introducing new techniques, equipment and materials, increasing the number of workers or machines, increasing the number of shifts, or acquiring additional production facilities.
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-planning] Capacity is calculated as (number of machines or workers) × (number of shifts) × (utilization) × (efficiency).
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-planning] They must all account both for current capacity as well as possible future scaling.
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-planning] The broad classes of capacity planning are lead strategy, lag strategy, match strategy, and adjustment strategy.
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-planning] Advantage of lead strategy: First, it ensures that the organization has adequate capacity to meet all demand, even during periods of high growth.
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-planning] This is especially important when the availability of a product or service is crucial, as in the case of emergency care or hot new product.
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-planning] For many new products, being late to market can mean the difference between success and failure.
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-planning] Another advantage of a lead capacity strategy is that it can be used to preempt competitors who might be planning to expand their own capacity.
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-planning] Being the first in an area to open a large grocery or home improvement store gives a retailer a define edge.
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-planning] Finally many businesses find that overbuilding in anticipation of increased usage is cheaper and less disruptive than constantly making small increases in capacity.
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-planning] Of course, a lead capacity strategy can be very risky, particularly if demand is unpredictable or technology is evolving rapidly.
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-planning] One simple model distinguishes between short-, mid-, and long-term capacity planning (operational, tactical, and strategical, respectively).
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-planning] These range from a few days to many years in the future.
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-planning] In the context of systems engineering, capacity planning is used during system design and system performance monitoring....
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-planning] Capacity planning is long-term decision that establishes a firm's overall level resources.
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-planning] It extends over a time horizon long enough to obtain resources.
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-planning] Capacity decisions affect the production lead time, customer responsiveness, operating cost and company ability to compete.
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-planning] Inadequate capacity planning can lead to the loss of the customer and business.
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-planning] Excess capacity can drain the company's resources and prevent investments into more lucrative ventures.
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-planning] The question of when capacity should be increased and by how much are the critical decisions.
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-planning] Failure to make these decisions correctly can be especially damaging to the overall performance when time delays are present in the system.
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-planning] From a scheduling perspective it is very easy to determine how much capacity (or time) will be required to manufacture a quantity of parts.
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-planning] Simply multiply the standard cycle time by the number of parts and divide by the part or process OEE %.
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-planning] (500 parts × 30 seconds) / 85% = 17647.1 seconds The OEE index makes it easy to determine whether we have ample capacity to run the required production.
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-planning] In this example 4.2 hours at standard versus 4.9 hours based on the OEE index.
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-planning] By repeating this process for all the parts that run through a given machine, it is possible to determine the total capacity required to run production.
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-planning] When considering new work for a piece of equipment or machinery, knowing how much capacity is available to run the work will eventually become part of the overall process.
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-planning] Typically, an annual forecast is used to determine how many hours per year are required.
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-planning] To calculate the total capacity available, the volume is adjusted according to the period being considered.
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-planning] The available capacity is the difference between the required capacity and planned operating capacity.
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-planning] Capacity is needed in formulation and execution of strategy as this refers to how capable are the resources in the organization.
[src:capacity-planning/capacity-planning] Without effective resources it could be very difficult to formulate and implement the Strategy.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Risk and uncertainty are central to forecasting and prediction; it is generally considered a good practice to indicate the degree of uncertainty attaching to forecasts.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] In any case, the data must be up to date in order for the forecast to be as accurate as possible.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] In some cases the data used to predict the variable of interest is itself forecast.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] A forecast is not to be confused with a Budget; budgets are more specific, fixed-term financial plans used for resource allocation and control, while forecasts provide estimates of future financial performance, allowing for flexibility and adaptability to changing circumstances.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Both tools are valuable in financial planning and decision-making, but they serve different functions.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Forecasting has applications in a wide range of fields where estimates of future conditions are useful.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Depending on the field, accuracy varies significantly.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] If the factors that relate to what is being forecast are known and well understood and there is a significant amount of data that can be used, it is likely the final value will be close to the forecast.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] If this is not the case or if the actual outcome is affected by the forecasts, the reliability of the forecasts can be significantly lower.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Climate change and increasing energy prices have led to the use of Egain Forecasting for buildings.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] This attempts to reduce the energy needed to heat the building, thus reducing the emission of greenhouse gases.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Forecasting is used in customer demand planning in everyday business for manufacturing and distribution companies.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] While the veracity of predictions for actual stock returns are disputed through reference to the efficient-market hypothesis, forecasting of broad economic trends is common.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Such analysis is provided by both non-profit groups as well as by for-profit private institutions.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Forecasting foreign exchange movements is typically achieved through a combination of historical and current data (summarized in charts) and fundamental analysis.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] An essential difference between chart analysis and fundamental economic analysis is that chartists study only the price action of a market, whereas fundamentalists attempt to look to the reasons behind the action.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Financial institutions assimilate the evidence provided by their fundamental and chartist researchers into one note to provide a final projection on the currency in question.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Forecasting has also been used to predict the development of conflict situations.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Forecasters perform research that uses empirical results to gauge the effectiveness of certain forecasting models.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] However research has shown that there is little difference between the accuracy of the forecasts of experts knowledgeable in the conflict situation and those by individuals who knew much less.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Similarly, experts in some studies argue that role thinking — standing in other people's shoes to forecast their decisions — does not contribute to the accuracy of the forecast.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] An important, albeit often ignored aspect of forecasting, is the relationship it holds with planning.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Forecasting can be described as predicting what the future *will* look like, whereas planning predicts what the future *should* look like.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] There is no single right forecasting method to use.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Selection of a method should be based on your objectives and your conditions (data etc.).
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] A good way to find a method is by visiting a selection tree.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] An example of a selection tree can be found here.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] In several cases, the forecast is either more or less than a prediction of the future.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Tetlock's *Superforecasting: The Art and Science of Prediction*, he discusses forecasting as a method of improving the ability to make decisions.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] A person can become better calibrated — *i.e.* having things they give 10% credence to happening 10% of the time.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Or they can forecast things more confidently — coming to the same conclusion but earlier.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Some have claimed that forecasting is a transferable skill with benefits to other areas of discussion and decision making.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Betting on sports or politics is another form of forecasting.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Rather than being used as advice, bettors are paid based on if they predicted correctly.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] While decisions might be made based on these bets (forecasts), the main motivation is generally financial.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Finally, futarchy is a form of government where forecasts of the impact of government action are used to decide which actions are taken.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Rather than advice, in futarchy's strongest form, the action with the best forecasted result is automatically taken.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Forecast improvement projects have been operated in a number of sectors: the National Hurricane Center's Hurricane Forecast Improvement Project (HFIP) and the Wind Forecast Improvement Project sponsored by the US Department of Energy are examples.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] In relation to supply chain management, the Du Pont model has been used to show that an increase in forecast accuracy can generate increases in sales and reductions in inventory, operating expenses and commitment of working capital.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Qualitative forecasting techniques are subjective, based on the opinion and judgment of consumers and experts; they are appropriate when past data are not available.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] They are usually applied to intermediate- or long-range decisions.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Examples of qualitative forecasting methods are informed opinion and judgment, the Delphi method, market research, and historical life-cycle analogy.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Quantitative forecasting models are used to forecast future data as a function of past data.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] They are appropriate to use when past numerical data is available and when it is reasonable to assume that some of the patterns in the data are expected to continue into the future.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] These methods are usually applied to short- or intermediate-range decisions.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Examples of quantitative forecasting methods are last period demand, simple and weighted N-Period moving averages, simple exponential smoothing, Poisson process model based forecasting and multiplicative seasonal indexes.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Previous research shows that different methods may lead to different level of forecasting accuracy.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] For example, GMDH neural network was found to have better forecasting performance than the classical forecasting algorithms such as Single Exponential Smooth, Double Exponential Smooth, ARIMA and back-propagation neural network.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] In this approach, the predictions of all future values are equal to the mean of the past data.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] This approach can be used with any sort of data where past data is available.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Although the time series notation has been used here, the average approach can also be used for cross-sectional data (when we are predicting unobserved values; values that are not included in the data set).
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Then, the prediction for unobserved values is the average of the observed values.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Naïve forecasts are the most cost-effective forecasting model, and provide a benchmark against which more sophisticated models can be compared.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] This forecasting method is only suitable for time series data.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Using the naïve approach, forecasts are produced that are equal to the last observed value.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] This method works quite well for economic and financial time series, which often have patterns that are difficult to reliably and accurately predict.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] If the time series is believed to have seasonality, the seasonal naïve approach may be more appropriate where the forecasts are equal to the value from last season.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] A variation on the naïve method is to allow the forecasts to increase or decrease over time, where the amount of change over time (called the drift) is set to be the average change seen in the historical data.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] This is equivalent to drawing a line between the first and last observation, and extrapolating it into the future.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] The seasonal naïve method accounts for seasonality by setting each prediction to be equal to the last observed value of the same season.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] For example, the prediction value for all subsequent months of April will be equal to the previous value observed for April.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] where m is the seasonal period (for example, for monthly data with yearly seasonality, $m=12$ ) and k is the integer part of $(h-1)/m$ .
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] The seasonal naïve method is particularly useful for data that has a very high level of seasonality.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] A deterministic approach is when there is no stochastic variable involved and the forecasts depend on the selected functions and parameters.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] where $\alpha ,\gamma ,\beta ,\mu ,\eta$ are some parameters.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] This approach has been proposed to simulate bursts of seemingly stochastic activity, interrupted by quieter periods.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] The assumption is that the presence of a strong deterministic ingredient is hidden by noise.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] The deterministic approach is noteworthy as it can reveal the underlying dynamical systems structure, which can be exploited for steering the dynamics into a desired regime.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Time series methods use historical data as the basis of estimating future outcomes.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] They are based on the assumption that past demand history is a good indicator of future demand.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Some forecasting methods try to identify the underlying factors that might influence the variable that is being forecast.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] For example, including information about climate patterns might improve the ability of a model to predict umbrella sales.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Forecasting models often take account of regular seasonal variations.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] In addition to climate, such variations can also be due to holidays and customs: for example, one might predict that sales of college football apparel will be higher during the football season than during the off season.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Several informal methods used in causal forecasting do not rely solely on the output of mathematical algorithms, but instead use the judgment of the forecaster.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Quantitative forecasting models are often judged against each other by comparing their in-sample or out-of-sample mean square error, although some researchers have advised against this.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Different forecasting approaches have different levels of accuracy.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] For example, it was found in one context that GMDH has higher forecasting accuracy than traditional ARIMA.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Judgmental forecasting methods incorporate intuitive judgement, opinions and subjective probability estimates.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Judgmental forecasting is used in cases where there is a lack of historical data or during completely new and unique market conditions.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Can be created with 3 points of a sequence and the "moment" or "index".
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] This type of extrapolation has 100% accuracy in predictions in a big percentage of known series database (OEIS).
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] where E is the forecast error at period t, Y is the actual value at period t, and F is the forecast for period t.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] A good forecasting method will yield residuals that are **uncorrelated**.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] If there are correlations between residual values, then there is information left in the residuals which should be used in computing forecasts.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] This can be accomplished by computing the expected value of a residual as a function of the known past residuals, and adjusting the forecast by the amount by which this expected value differs from zero.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] A good forecasting method will also have **zero mean**.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] If the residuals have a mean other than zero, then the forecasts are biased and can be improved by adjusting the forecasting technique by an additive constant that equals the mean of the unadjusted residuals.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] The forecast error, E, is on the same scale as the data, as such, these accuracy measures are scale-dependent and cannot be used to make comparisons between series on different scales.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] These are more frequently used to compare forecast performance between different data sets because they are scale-independent.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] However, they have the disadvantage of being extremely large or undefined if Y is close to or equal to zero.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Hyndman and Koehler (2006) proposed using scaled errors as an alternative to percentage errors.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Business forecasters and practitioners sometimes use different terminology.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] They refer to the PMAD as the MAPE, although they compute this as a volume weighted MAPE.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] For more information, see Calculating demand forecast accuracy.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] When comparing the accuracy of different forecasting methods on a specific data set, the measures of aggregate error are compared with each other and the method that yields the lowest error is preferred.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] When evaluating the quality of forecasts, it is invalid to look at how well a model fits the historical data; the accuracy of forecasts can only be determined by considering how well a model performs on new data that were not used when fitting the model.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] When choosing models, it is common to use a portion of the available data for fitting, and use the rest of the data for testing the model, as was done in the above examples.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Cross-validation is a more sophisticated version of training a test set.
