[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Compute the forecast accuracy measures based on the errors obtained.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] For time series data, the training set can only include observations prior to the test set.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Therefore, no future observations can be used in constructing the forecast.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Repeat the above step for *i* = 2,...,*T–k* where *T* is the total number of observations.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Compute the forecast accuracy over all errors.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] This procedure is sometimes known as a "rolling forecasting origin" because the "origin" (*k+i -1)* at which the forecast is based rolls forward in time.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Further, two-step-ahead or in general *p*-step-ahead forecasts can be computed by first forecasting the value immediately after the training set, then using this value with the training set values to forecast two periods ahead, etc.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Some authors distinguish **forecastability** from **forecast accuracy**.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] In this usage, forecastability refers to the inherent predictability of a time series or process, while forecast accuracy refers to the performance of a particular forecasting method applied to it.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Forecastability has also been discussed as a structural property of time series related to regularity and predictability.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Seasonality is a characteristic of a time series in which the data experiences regular and predictable changes which recur every calendar year.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Any predictable change or pattern in a time series that recurs or repeats over a one-year period can be said to be seasonal.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] It is common in many situations – such as grocery store or even in a Medical Examiner's office—that the demand depends on the day of the week.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] An index higher than 1 indicates that demand is higher than average; an index less than 1 indicates that the demand is less than the average.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] The cyclic behaviour of data takes place when there are regular fluctuations in the data which usually last for an interval of at least two years, and when the length of the current cycle cannot be predetermined.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Cyclic behavior is not to be confused with seasonal behavior.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Seasonal fluctuations follow a consistent pattern each year so the period is always known.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] As an example, during the Christmas period, inventories of stores tend to increase in order to prepare for Christmas shoppers.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] As an example of cyclic behaviour, the population of a particular natural ecosystem will exhibit cyclic behaviour when the population decreases as its natural food source decreases, and once the population is low, the food source will recover and the population will start to increase again.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Cyclic data cannot be accounted for using ordinary seasonal adjustment since it is not of fixed period.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Limitations pose barriers beyond which forecasting methods cannot reliably predict.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] There are many events and values that cannot be forecast reliably.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Events such as the roll of a die or the results of the lottery cannot be forecast because they are random events and there is no significant relationship in the data.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] The concept of "self-destructing predictions" concerns the way in which some predictions can undermine themselves by influencing social behavior.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] This is because "predictors are part of the social context about which they are trying to make a prediction and may influence that context in the process".
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] For example, a forecast that a large percentage of a population will become HIV infected based on existing trends may cause more people to avoid risky behavior and thus reduce the HIV infection rate, invalidating the forecast (which might have remained correct if it had not been publicly known).
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Or, a prediction that cybersecurity will become a major issue may cause organizations to implement more security cybersecurity measures, thus limiting the issue.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] As proposed by Edward Lorenz in 1963, long range weather forecasts, those made at a range of two weeks or more, are impossible to definitively predict the state of the atmosphere, owing to the chaotic nature of the fluid dynamics equations involved.
[src:capacity-planning/forecasting] Extremely small errors in the initial input, such as temperatures and winds, within numerical models double every five days.
[src:capacity-planning/little-s-law] The relationship is not influenced by the arrival process distribution, the service distribution, the service order, or practically anything else.
[src:capacity-planning/little-s-law] In most queuing systems, service time is the bottleneck that creates the queue.
[src:capacity-planning/little-s-law] The result applies to any system, and particularly, it applies to systems within systems.
[src:capacity-planning/little-s-law] For example in a bank branch, the customer line might be one subsystem, and each of the tellers another subsystem, and Little's result could be applied to each one, as well as the whole thing.
[src:capacity-planning/little-s-law] The only requirement is that the system be ergodic.
[src:capacity-planning/little-s-law] In some cases it is possible not only to mathematically relate the *average* number in the system to the *average* wait but even to relate the entire *probability distribution* (and moments) of the number in the system to the wait.
[src:capacity-planning/little-s-law] In a 1954 paper, Little's law was assumed true and used without proof.
[src:capacity-planning/little-s-law] The form *L* = *λW* was first published by Philip M.
[src:capacity-planning/little-s-law] Morse where he challenged readers to find a situation where the relationship did not hold.
[src:capacity-planning/little-s-law] Little published in 1961 his proof of the law, showing that no such situation existed.
[src:capacity-planning/little-s-law] Little's proof was followed by a simpler version by Jewell and another by Eilon.
[src:capacity-planning/little-s-law] Shaler Stidham published a different and more intuitive proof in 1972.
[src:capacity-planning/little-s-law] Imagine an application that had no easy way to measure response time.
[src:capacity-planning/little-s-law] For example: A queue depth meter shows an average of nine jobs waiting to be serviced.
[src:capacity-planning/little-s-law] Add one for the job being serviced, so there is an average of ten jobs in the system.
[src:capacity-planning/little-s-law] Another meter shows a mean throughput of 50 per second.
[src:capacity-planning/little-s-law] The mean response time is calculated as 0.2 seconds = 10 / 50 per second.
[src:capacity-planning/little-s-law] Imagine a small store with a single counter and an area for browsing, where only one person can be at the counter at a time, and no one leaves without buying something.
[src:capacity-planning/little-s-law] If the rate at which people enter the store (called the arrival rate) is the rate at which they exit (called the exit rate), the system is stable.
[src:capacity-planning/little-s-law] By contrast, an arrival rate exceeding an exit rate would represent an unstable system, where the number of waiting customers in the store would gradually increase towards infinity.
[src:capacity-planning/little-s-law] Assume customers arrive at the rate of 10 per hour and stay an average of 0.5 hour.
[src:capacity-planning/little-s-law] This means we should find the average number of customers in the store at any time to be 5.
[src:capacity-planning/little-s-law] Now suppose the store is considering doing more advertising to raise the arrival rate to 20 per hour.
[src:capacity-planning/little-s-law] The store must either be prepared to host an average of 10 occupants or must reduce the time each customer spends in the store to 0.25 hour.
[src:capacity-planning/little-s-law] The store might achieve the latter by ringing up the bill faster or by adding more counters.
[src:capacity-planning/little-s-law] We can apply Little's Law to systems within the store.
[src:capacity-planning/little-s-law] For example, consider the counter and its queue.
[src:capacity-planning/little-s-law] Assume we notice that there are on average 2 customers in the queue and at the counter.
[src:capacity-planning/little-s-law] We know the arrival rate is 10 per hour, so customers must be spending 0.2 hours on average checking out.
[src:capacity-planning/little-s-law] We can even apply Little's Law to the counter itself.
[src:capacity-planning/little-s-law] The average number of people at the counter would be in the range (0, 1) since no more than one person can be at the counter at a time.
[src:capacity-planning/little-s-law] In that case, the average number of people at the counter is also known as the utilisation of the counter.
[src:capacity-planning/little-s-law] However, because a store in reality generally has a limited amount of space, it can eventually become unstable.
[src:capacity-planning/little-s-law] If the arrival rate is much greater than the exit rate, the store will eventually start to overflow, and thus any new arriving customers will simply be rejected (and forced to go somewhere else or try again later) until there is once again free space available in the store.
[src:capacity-planning/little-s-law] This is also the difference between the *arrival rate* and the *effective arrival rate*, where the arrival rate roughly corresponds to the rate at which customers arrive at the store, whereas the effective arrival rate corresponds to the rate at which customers *enter* the store.
[src:capacity-planning/little-s-law] However, in a system with an infinite size and no loss, the two are equal.
[src:capacity-planning/little-s-law] Little's law is widely used in manufacturing to predict lead time based on the production rate and the amount of work-in-process.
[src:capacity-planning/little-s-law] Software-performance testers have used Little's law to ensure that the observed performance results are not due to bottlenecks imposed by the testing apparatus.
[src:capacity-planning/little-s-law] Other applications include staffing emergency departments in hospitals.
[src:capacity-planning/little-s-law] Lastly, an equivalent version of Little's law also applies in the fields of demography and population biology, although not referred to as "Little's Law".
[src:capacity-planning/little-s-law] For example, Cohen (2008) explains that in a homogeneous stationary population without migration, $P=B\times e$ , where P is the total population size, B is the number of births per year, and e is the life expectancy from birth.
[src:capacity-planning/little-s-law] The formula $P=B\times e$ is thus directly equivalent to Little's law ( $L=\lambda \times W$ ).
[src:capacity-planning/little-s-law] However, biological populations tend to be dynamic and therefore more complicated to model accurately.
[src:capacity-planning/little-s-law] In some cases, it is possible not only to relate averages but to relate the entire probability distribution of the number in the system to the time in the system under a first come, first served discipline.
[src:capacity-planning/little-s-law] A distributional relation for many FIFO/Poisson-class systems was derived by Keilson and Servi (1988) and further developed in related work, including links to the Fuhrmann–Cooper decomposition; later, Bertsimas and Nakazato (1995) provided a new proof and surveyed applications.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] Queueing theory has its origins in research by Agner Krarup Erlang, who created models to describe the system of incoming calls at the Copenhagen Telephone Exchange Company.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] These ideas were seminal to the field of teletraffic engineering and have since seen applications in telecommunications, traffic engineering, computing, project management, and particularly industrial engineering, where they are applied in the design of factories, shops, offices, and hospitals.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] Queueing theory is one of the major areas of study in the discipline of management science.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] Through management science, businesses are able to solve a variety of problems using different scientific and mathematical approaches.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] Queueing analysis is the probabilistic analysis of waiting lines, and thus the results, also referred to as the operating characteristics, are probabilistic rather than deterministic.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] The overall goal of queueing analysis is to compute these characteristics for the current system and then test several alternatives that could lead to improvement.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] Computing the operating characteristics for the current system and comparing the values to the characteristics of the alternative systems allows managers to see the pros and cons of each potential option.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] These systems help in the final decision making process by showing ways to increase savings, reduce waiting time, improve efficiency, etc.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] The main queueing models that can be used are the single-server waiting line system and the multiple-server waiting line system, which are discussed further below.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] These models can be further differentiated depending on whether service times are constant or undefined, the queue length is finite, the calling population is finite, etc.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] A *queue* or *queueing node* can be thought of as nearly a black box.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] *Jobs* (also called *customers* or *requests*, depending on the field) arrive to the queue, possibly wait some time, take some time being processed, and then depart from the queue.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] However, the queueing node is not quite a pure black box since some information is needed about the inside of the queueing node.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] The queue has one or more *servers* which can each be paired with an arriving job.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] When the job is completed and departs, that server will again be free to be paired with another arriving job.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] An analogy often used is that of the cashier at a supermarket.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] Customers arrive, are processed by the cashier, and depart.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] Each cashier processes one customer at a time, and hence this is a queueing node with only one server.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] A setting where a customer will leave immediately if the cashier is busy when the customer arrives, is referred to as a queue with no *buffer* (or no *waiting area*).
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] A setting with a waiting zone for up to *n* customers is called a queue with a buffer of size *n*.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] The behaviour of a single queue (also called a *queueing node*) can be described by a birth–death process, which describes the arrivals and departures from the queue, along with the number of jobs currently in the system.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] If *k* denotes the number of jobs in the system (either being serviced or waiting if the queue has a buffer of waiting jobs), then an arrival increases *k* by 1 and a departure decreases *k* by 1.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] The system transitions between values of *k* by *births* and *deaths*, which occur at the arrival rates $\lambda _{i}$ and the departure rates $\mu _{i}$ for each job i .
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] For a queue, these rates are generally considered not to vary with the number of jobs in the queue, so a single average rate of arrivals/departures per unit time is assumed.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] The steady state equations for the birth-and-death process, known as the balance equations, are as follows.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] Here $P_{n}$ denotes the steady state probability to be in state *n*.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] which, together with the equation for $P_{n}$ $(n\geq 1)$ , fully describes the required steady state probabilities.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] Single queueing nodes are usually described using Kendall's notation in the form A/S/*c* where *A* describes the distribution of durations between each arrival to the queue, *S* the distribution of service times for jobs, and *c* the number of servers at the node.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] For an example of the notation, the M/M/1 queue is a simple model where a single server serves jobs that arrive according to a Poisson process (where inter-arrival durations are exponentially distributed) and have exponentially distributed service times (the M denotes a Markov process).
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] In an M/G/1 queue, the G stands for *general* and indicates an arbitrary probability distribution for service times.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] Further, let $E_{n}$ represent the number of times the system enters state *n*, and $L_{n}$ represent the number of times the system leaves state *n*.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] That is, the number of times the system leaves a state differs by at most 1 from the number of times it enters that state, since it will either return into that state at some time in the future ( $E_{n}=L_{n}$ ) or not ( $\left\vert E_{n}-L_{n}\right\vert =1$ ).
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] When the system arrives at a steady state, the arrival rate should be equal to the departure rate.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] A common basic queueing system is attributed to Erlang and is a modification of Little's Law.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] Assuming an exponential distribution for the rates, the waiting time *W* can be defined as the proportion of arrivals that are served.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] The two-stage one-box model is common in epidemiology.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] In 1909, Agner Krarup Erlang, a Danish engineer who worked for the Copenhagen Telephone Exchange, published the first paper on what would now be called queueing theory.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] He modeled the number of telephone calls arriving at an exchange by a Poisson process and solved the M/D/1 queue in 1917 and M/D/*k* queueing model in 1920.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] If the node has more jobs than servers, then jobs will queue and wait for service.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] The M/G/1 queue was solved by Felix Pollaczek in 1930, a solution later recast in probabilistic terms by Aleksandr Khinchin and now known as the Pollaczek–Khinchine formula.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] After the 1940s, queueing theory became an area of research interest to mathematicians.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] In 1953, David George Kendall solved the GI/M/*k* queue and introduced the modern notation for queues, now known as Kendall's notation.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] In 1957, Pollaczek studied the GI/G/1 using an integral equation.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] John Kingman gave a formula for the mean waiting time in a G/G/1 queue, now known as Kingman's formula.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] Leonard Kleinrock worked on the application of queueing theory to message switching in the early 1960s and packet switching in the early 1970s.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] His initial contribution to this field was his doctoral thesis at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology in 1962, published in book form in 1964.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] His theoretical work published in the early 1970s underpinned the use of packet switching in the ARPANET, a forerunner to the Internet.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] The matrix geometric method and matrix analytic methods have allowed queues with phase-type distributed inter-arrival and service time distributions to be considered.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] Systems with coupled orbits are an important part in queueing theory in the application to wireless networks and signal processing.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] Modern day application of queueing theory concerns among other things product development where (material) products have a spatiotemporal existence, in the sense that products have a certain volume and a certain duration.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] Problems such as performance metrics for the M/G/*k* queue remain an open problem.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] this principle states that customers are served one at a time and that the customer that has been waiting the longest is served first.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] Service capacity is shared equally between customers.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] (ROS), this discipline states that the next job served is selected at random from the jobs waiting in the queue.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] Customers with high priority are served first.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] (where a job in service can be interrupted by a higher-priority job).
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] The next job to be served is the one with the smallest size.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] The next job to be served is the one with the smallest original size.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] The next job to serve is the one with the smallest remaining processing requirement.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] Server failures occur according to a stochastic (random) process (usually Poisson) and are followed by setup periods during which the server is unavailable.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] The interrupted customer remains in the service area until server is fixed.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] Arriving customers not served (either due to the queue having no buffer, or due to balking or reneging by the customer) are also known as *dropouts*.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] The average rate of dropouts is a significant parameter describing a queue.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] Queue networks are systems in which multiple queues are connected by *customer routing*.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] When a customer is serviced at one node, it can join another node and queue for service, or leave the network.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] For networks of *m* nodes, the state of the system can be described by an *m*–dimensional vector (*x*1, *x*2, ..., *x**m*) where *x**i* represents the number of customers at each node.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] The simplest non-trivial networks of queues are called tandem queues.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] The first significant results in this area were Jackson networks, for which an efficient product-form stationary distribution exists and the mean value analysis (which allows average metrics such as throughput and sojourn times) can be computed.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] If the total number of customers in the network remains constant, the network is called a *closed network* and has been shown to also have a product–form stationary distribution by the Gordon–Newell theorem.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] This result was extended to the BCMP network, where a network with very general service time, regimes, and customer routing is shown to also exhibit a product–form stationary distribution.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] The normalizing constant can be calculated with the Buzen's algorithm, proposed in 1973.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] Networks of customers have also been investigated, such as Kelly networks, where customers of different classes experience different priority levels at different service nodes.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] Another type of network are G-networks, first proposed by Erol Gelenbe in 1993: these networks do not assume exponential time distributions like the classic Jackson network.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] In discrete-time networks where there is a constraint on which service nodes can be active at any time, the max-weight scheduling algorithm chooses a service policy to give optimal throughput in the case that each job visits only a single-person service node.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] In the more general case where jobs can visit more than one node, backpressure routing gives optimal throughput.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] A network scheduler must choose a queueing algorithm, which affects the characteristics of the larger network.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] Mean-field models consider the limiting behaviour of the empirical measure (proportion of queues in different states) as the number of queues *m* approaches infinity.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] The impact of other queues on any given queue in the network is approximated by a differential equation.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] The deterministic model converges to the same stationary distribution as the original model.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] In a system with high occupancy rates (utilisation near 1), a heavy traffic approximation can be used to approximate the queueing length process by a reflected Brownian motion, Ornstein–Uhlenbeck process, or more general diffusion process.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] The number of dimensions of the Brownian process is equal to the number of queueing nodes, with the diffusion restricted to the non-negative orthant.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] Fluid models are continuous deterministic analogs of queueing networks obtained by taking the limit when the process is scaled in time and space, allowing heterogeneous objects.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] This scaled trajectory converges to a deterministic equation which allows the stability of the system to be proven.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] It is known that a queueing network can be stable but have an unstable fluid limit.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] Queueing theory finds widespread application in computer science and information technology.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] In networking, for instance, queues are integral to routers and switches, where packets queue up for transmission.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] By applying queueing theory principles, designers can optimize these systems, ensuring responsive performance and efficient resource utilization.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] Beyond the technological realm, queueing theory is relevant to everyday experiences.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] Whether waiting in line at a supermarket or for public transportation, understanding the principles of queueing theory provides valuable insights into optimizing these systems for enhanced user satisfaction.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] At some point, everyone will be involved in an aspect of queuing.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] What some may view to be an inconvenience could possibly be the most effective method.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] Queueing theory, a discipline rooted in applied mathematics and computer science, is a field dedicated to the study and analysis of queues, or waiting lines, and their implications across a diverse range of applications.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] This theoretical framework has proven instrumental in understanding and optimizing the efficiency of systems characterized by the presence of queues.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] The study of queues is essential in contexts such as traffic systems, computer networks, telecommunications, and service operations.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] Queueing theory delves into various foundational concepts, with the arrival process and service process being central.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] The arrival process describes the manner in which entities join the queue over time, often modeled using stochastic processes like Poisson processes.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] The efficiency of queueing systems is gauged through key performance metrics.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] These include the average queue length, average wait time, and system throughput.
[src:capacity-planning/queueing-theory] These metrics provide insights into the system's functionality, guiding decisions aimed at enhancing performance and reducing wait times.
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] In an economic context, a scalable business model implies that a company can increase sales given increased resources.
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] For example, a package delivery system is scalable because more packages can be delivered by adding more delivery vehicles.
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] However, if all packages had to first pass through a single warehouse for sorting, the system would not be as scalable, because one warehouse can handle only a limited number of packages.
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] In computing, scalability is a characteristic of computers, networks, algorithms, networking protocols, programs and applications.
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] An example is a search engine, which must support increasing numbers of users, and the number of topics it indexes.
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] **Webscale** is a computer architectural approach that brings the capabilities of large-scale cloud computing companies into enterprise data centers.
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] In distributed systems, there are several definitions according to the authors, some considering the concepts of scalability a sub-part of elasticity, others as being distinct.
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] According to Marc Brooker: "a system is scalable in the range where marginal cost of additional workload is nearly constant." Serverless technologies fit this definition but you need to consider total cost of ownership not just the infra cost.
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] In mathematics, scalability mostly refers to closure under scalar multiplication.
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] In industrial engineering and manufacturing, scalability refers to the capacity of a process, system, or organization to handle a growing workload, adapt to increasing demands, and maintain operational efficiency.
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] A scalable system can effectively manage increased production volumes, new product lines, or expanding markets without compromising quality or performance.
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] In this context, scalability is a vital consideration for businesses aiming to meet customer expectations, remain competitive, and achieve sustainable growth.
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] Factors influencing scalability include the flexibility of the production process, the adaptability of the workforce, and the integration of advanced technologies.
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] By implementing scalable solutions, companies can optimize resource utilization, reduce costs, and streamline their operations.
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] Scalability in industrial engineering and manufacturing enables businesses to respond to fluctuating market conditions, capitalize on emerging opportunities, and thrive in an ever-evolving global landscape.
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] The Incident Command System (ICS) is used by emergency response agencies in the United States.
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] ICS can scale resource coordination from a single-engine roadside brushfire to an interstate wildfire.
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] The first resource on scene establishes command, with authority to order resources and delegate responsibility (managing five to seven officers, who will again delegate to up to seven, and on as the incident grows).
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] As an incident expands, more senior officers assume command.
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] Resources fall into two broad categories: horizontal and vertical.
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] Scaling horizontally (out/in) means adding or removing nodes, such as adding a new computer to a distributed software application.
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] An example might involve scaling out from one web server to three.
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] High-performance computing applications, such as seismic analysis and biotechnology, scale workloads horizontally to support tasks that once would have required expensive supercomputers.
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] Other workloads, such as large social networks, exceed the capacity of the largest supercomputer and can only be handled by scalable systems.
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] Exploiting this scalability requires software for efficient resource management and maintenance.
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] Scaling vertically (up/down) means adding resources to (or removing resources from) a single node, typically involving the addition of CPUs, memory or storage to a single computer.
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] Benefits to scale-up include avoiding increased management complexity, more sophisticated programming to allocate tasks among resources and handling issues such as throughput, latency, and synchronization across nodes.
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] Moreover some applications do not scale horizontally.
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] Network function virtualization defines these terms differently: scaling out/in is the ability to scale by adding/removing resource instances (e.g., virtual machine), whereas scaling up/down is the ability to scale by changing allocated resources (e.g., memory/CPU/storage capacity).
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] Scalability for databases requires that the database system be able to perform additional work given greater hardware resources, such as additional servers, processors, memory and storage.
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] Workloads have continued to grow and demands on databases have followed suit.
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] Algorithmic innovations include row-level locking and table and index partitioning.
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] Architectural innovations include shared-nothing and shared-everything architectures for managing multi-server configurations.
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] In the context of scale-out data storage, scalability is defined as the maximum storage cluster size which guarantees full data consistency, meaning there is only ever one valid version of stored data in the whole cluster, independently from the number of redundant physical data copies.
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] Clusters which provide "lazy" redundancy by updating copies in an asynchronous fashion are called 'eventually consistent'.
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] This type of scale-out design is suitable when availability and responsiveness are rated higher than consistency, which is true for many web file-hosting services or web caches (*if you want the latest version, wait some seconds for it to propagate*).
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] For all classical transaction-oriented applications, this design should be avoided.
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] Many open-source and even commercial scale-out storage clusters, especially those built on top of standard PC hardware and networks, provide eventual consistency only, such as some NoSQL databases like CouchDB and others mentioned above.
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] Write operations invalidate other copies, but often don't wait for their acknowledgements.
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] Read operations typically don't check every redundant copy prior to answering, potentially missing the preceding write operation.
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] The large amount of metadata signal traffic would require specialized hardware and short distances to be handled with acceptable performance (i.e., act like a non-clustered storage device or database).
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] It is often advised to focus system design on hardware scalability rather than on capacity.
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] It is typically cheaper to add a new node to a system in order to achieve improved performance than to partake in performance tuning to improve the capacity that each node can handle.
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] But this approach can have diminishing returns (as discussed in performance engineering).
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] For example: suppose 70% of a program can be sped up if parallelized and run on multiple CPUs instead of one.
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] Doubling the processing power has only sped up the process by roughly one-fifth.
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] If the whole problem was parallelizable, the speed would also double.
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] Therefore, throwing in more hardware is not necessarily the optimal approach.
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] In distributed systems, you can use Universal Scalability Law (USL) to model and to optimize scalability of your system.
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] Gunther and quantifies scalability based on parameters such as contention and coherency.
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] Contention refers to delay due to waiting or queueing for shared resources.
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] Coherence refers to delay for data to become consistent.
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] For example, having a high contention indicates sequential processing that could be parallelized, while having a high coherency suggests excessive dependencies among processes, prompting you to minimize interactions.
[src:capacity-planning/scalability] Also, with help of USL, you can, in advance, calculate the maximum effective capacity of your system: scaling up your system beyond that point is a waste.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Ask someone to name a Google software engineering effort and they’ll likely list a consumer-facing product like Gmail or Maps; some might even mention underlying infrastructure such as Bigtable or Colossus.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] But in truth, there is a massive amount of behind-the-scenes software engineering that consumers never see.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] A number of those products are developed within SRE.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Google’s production environment is—by some measures—one of the most complex machines humanity has ever built.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] SREs have firsthand experience with the intricacies of production, making them uniquely well suited to develop the appropriate tools to solve internal problems and use cases related to keeping production running.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] The majority of these tools are related to the overall directive of maintaining uptime and keeping latency low, but take many forms: examples include binary rollout mechanisms, monitoring, or a development environment built on dynamic server composition.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Overall, these SRE-developed tools are full-fledged software engineering projects, distinct from one-off solutions and quick hacks, and the SREs who develop them have adopted a product-based mindset that takes both internal customers and a roadmap for future plans into account.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] In many ways, the vast scale of Google production has necessitated internal software development, because few third-party tools are designed at sufficient scale for Google’s needs.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] The company’s history of successful software projects has led us to appreciate the benefits of developing directly within SRE.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] From a purely pragmatic standpoint, Google clearly benefits from having engineers with SRE experience developing software.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Having the people with direct experience running production systems developing the tools that will ultimately contribute to uptime and latency goals makes a lot of sense.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] On the flip side, individual SREs, as well as the broader SRE organization, also benefit from SRE-driven software development.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Fully fledged software development projects within SRE provide career development opportunities for SREs, as well as an outlet for engineers who don’t want their coding skills to get rusty.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Long-term project work provides much-needed balance to interrupts and on-call work, and can provide job satisfaction for engineers who want their careers to maintain a balance between software engineering and systems engineering.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Beyond the design of automation tools and other efforts to reduce the workload for engineers in SRE, software development projects can further benefit the SRE organization by attracting and helping to retain engineers with a broad variety of skills.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] The desirability of team diversity is doubly true for SRE, where a variety of backgrounds and problem-solving approaches can help prevent blind spots.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] To this end, Google always strives to staff its SRE teams with a mix of engineers with traditional software development experience and engineers with systems engineering experience.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] This case study examines Auxon, a powerful tool developed within SRE to automate capacity planning for services running in Google production.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] To best understand how Auxon was conceived and the problems it addresses, we’ll first examine the problem space associated with capacity planning, and the difficulties that traditional approaches to this task present for services at Google and across the industry as a whole.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] For more context on how Google uses the terms *service* and *cluster*, see The Production Environment at Google, from the Viewpoint of an SRE.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] When and where are these resources needed?
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Given this forecasted outlook, what’s the best way to meet this demand with additional supply of resources?
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Does the plan line up with budgetary, product-level, and technical considerations?
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Once resources eventually arrive (potentially in phases over the course of some defined period of time), which services get to use the resources?
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] How do I make typically lower-level resources (CPU, disk, etc.) useful for services?
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] It bears stressing that capacity planning is a neverending *cycle*: assumptions change, deployments slip, and budgets are cut, resulting in revision upon revision of The Plan.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] And each revision has trickle-down effects that must propagate throughout the plans of all subsequent quarters.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] For example, a shortfall this quarter must be made up in future quarters.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Traditional capacity planning uses demand as a key driver, and manually shapes supply to fit demand in response to each change.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Traditional capacity planning produces a resource allocation plan that can be disrupted by any seemingly minor change.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Minor changes require cross-checking the entire allocation plan to make sure that the plan is still feasible; larger changes (such as delayed resource delivery or product strategy changes) potentially require re-creating the plan from scratch.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] A delivery slippage in a single cluster might impact the redundancy or latency requirements of multiple services: resource allocations in other clusters must be increased to make up for the slippage, and these and any other changes would have to propagate throughout the plan.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Also, consider that the capacity plan for any given quarter (or other time frame) is based on the expected outcome of the capacity plans of previous quarters, meaning that a change in any one quarter results in work to update subsequent quarters.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] For many teams, the process of collecting the data necessary to generate demand forecasts is slow and error-prone.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] And when it is time to find capacity to meet this future demand, not all resources are equally suitable.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] For example, if latency requirements mean that a service must commit to serve user demand on the same continent as the user, obtaining additional resources in North America won’t alleviate a capacity shortfall in Asia.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Every forecast has *constraints*, or parameters around how it can be fulfilled; constraints are fundamentally related to intent, which is discussed in the next section.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Mapping constrained resource requests into allocations of actual resources from the available capacity is equally slow: it’s both complex and tedious to bin pack requests into limited space by hand, or to find solutions that fit a limited budget.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] This process may already paint a grim picture, but to make matters worse, the tools it requires are typically unreliable or cumbersome.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Spreadsheets suffer severely from scalability problems and have limited error-checking abilities.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Data becomes stale, and tracking changes becomes difficult.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Teams often are forced to make simplifying assumptions and reduce the complexity of their requirements, simply to render maintaining adequate capacity a tractable problem.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] When service owners face the challenges of fitting a series of requests for capacity from various services into the resources available to them, in a manner that meets the various constraints a service may have, additional imprecision ensues.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Bin packing is an NP-hard problem that is difficult for human beings to compute by hand.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Furthermore, the capacity request from a service is generally an inflexible set of demand requirements: *X* cores in cluster *Y*.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] The reasons why *X* cores or *Y* cluster are needed, and any degrees of freedom around those parameters, are long lost by the time the request reaches a human trying to fit a list of demands into available supply.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] The net result is a massive expenditure of human effort to come up with a bin packing that is approximate, at best.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] The process is brittle to change, and there are no known bounds on an optimal solution.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] At Google, many teams have moved to an approach we call *Intent-based Capacity Planning*.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] The basic premise of this approach is to programmatically encode the dependencies and parameters (*intent*) of a service’s needs, and use that encoding to autogenerate an allocation plan that details which resources go to which service, in which cluster.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] If demand, supply, or service requirements change, we can simply autogenerate a new plan in response to the changed parameters, which is now the new best distribution of resources.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] With a service’s true requirements and flexibility captured, the capacity plan is now dramatically more nimble in the face of change, and we can reach an optimal solution that meets as many parameters as possible.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] With bin packing delegated to computers, human toil is drastically reduced, and service owners can focus on high-order priorities like SLOs, production dependencies, and service infrastructure requirements, as opposed to low-level scrounging for resources.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] As an added benefit, using computational optimization to map from intent to implementation achieves much greater precision, ultimately resulting in cost savings to the organization.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Bin packing is still far from a solved problem, because certain types are still considered NP-hard; however, today’s algorithms can solve to a known optimal solution.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] why do we need this many resources specifically in these particular clusters?
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] This request introduces more degrees of freedom and is potentially easier to fulfill, although it doesn’t explain the reasoning behind its requirements.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] why do we need this quantity of resources, and why 3 footprints?
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Suddenly greater flexibility is introduced and we can understand at a more "human" level what happens if service Foo does not receive these resources.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] This is a more abstract requirement, and the ramification if the requirement isn’t met becomes clear: reliability will suffer.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] + 2 is not actually sufficient or optimal for this service, and some other deployment plan would be more suitable.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] So what level of intent should be used by intent-driven capacity planning?
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Ideally, all levels of intent should be supported together, with services benefiting the more they shift to specifying intent versus implementation.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] In Google’s experience, services tend to achieve the best wins as they cross to step 3: good degrees of flexibility are available, and the ramifications of this request are in higher-level and understandable terms.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Particularly sophisticated services may aim for step 4.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] What information do we need in order to capture a service’s intent?
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Enter dependencies, performance metrics, and prioritization.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Services at Google depend on many other infrastructure and user-facing services, and these dependencies heavily influence where a service can be placed.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] For example, imagine user-facing service Foo, which depends upon Bar, an infrastructure storage service.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Foo expresses a requirement that Bar must be located within 30 milliseconds of network latency of Foo.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] This requirement has important repercussions for where we place both Foo *and* Bar, and intent-driven capacity planning must take these constraints into account.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Furthermore, production dependencies are nested: to build upon the preceding example, imagine service Bar has its own dependencies on Baz, a lower-level distributed storage service, and Qux, an application management service.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Therefore, where we can now place Foo depends on where we can place Bar, Baz, and Qux.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] A given set of production dependencies can be shared, possibly with different stipulations around intent.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Demand for one service trickles down to result in demand for one or more other services.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Understanding the chain of dependencies helps formulate the general scope of the bin packing problem, but we still need more information about expected resource usage.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] How many compute resources does service Foo need to serve *N* user queries?
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] For every *N* queries of service Foo, how many Mbps of data do we expect for service Bar?
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Performance metrics are the glue between dependencies.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] They convert from one or more higher-level resource type(s) to one or more lower-level resource type(s).
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Deriving appropriate performance metrics for a service can involve load testing and resource usage monitoring.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Inevitably, resource constraints result in trade-offs and hard decisions: of the many requirements that all services have, which requirements should be sacrificed in the face of insufficient capacity?
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Perhaps *N* + 2 redundancy for service Foo is more important than *N* + 1 redundancy for service Bar.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Or perhaps the feature launch of *X* is less important than *N* + 0 redundancy for service Baz.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Intent-driven planning forces these decisions to be made transparently, openly, and consistently.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Resource constraints entail the same trade-offs, but all too often, the prioritization can be ad hoc and opaque to service owners.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Intent-based planning allows prioritization to be as granular or coarse as needed.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Auxon is a perfect case study to demonstrate how software development can be fostered within SRE.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Auxon is actively used to plan the use of many millions of dollars of machine resources at Google.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] It has become a critical component of capacity planning for several major divisions within Google.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] As a product, Auxon provides the means to collect intent-based descriptions of a service’s resource requirements and dependencies.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] These user intents are expressed as requirements for how the owner would like the service to be provisioned.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Requirements can be prioritized, a feature that’s useful if resources are insufficient to meet all requirements, and therefore trade-offs must be made.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] These requirements—the intent—are ultimately represented internally as a giant mixed-integer or linear program.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Auxon solves the linear program, and uses the resultant bin packing solution to formulate an allocation plan for resources.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Figure 18-1 and the explanations that follow it outline Auxon’s major components.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Auxon was first imagined by an SRE and a technical program manager who had separately been tasked by their respective teams with capacity planning large portions of Google’s infrastructure.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Having performed manual capacity planning in spreadsheets, they were well positioned to understand the inefficiencies and opportunities for improvement through automation, and the features such a tool might require.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Throughout Auxon’s development, the SRE team behind the product continued to be deeply involved in the production world.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] The team maintained a role in on-call rotations for several of Google’s services, and participated in design discussions and technical leadership of these services.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Through these ongoing interactions, the team was able to stay grounded in the production world: they acted as both the consumer and developer of their own product.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] When the product failed, the team was directly impacted.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Feature requests were informed through the team’s own firsthand experiences.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Not only did firsthand experience of the problem space buy a huge sense of ownership in the product’s success, but it also helped give the product credibility and legitimacy within SRE.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Don’t focus on perfection and purity of solution, especially if the bounds of the problem aren’t well known.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Any sufficiently complex software engineering effort is bound to encounter uncertainty as to how a component should be designed or how a problem should be tackled.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Auxon met with such uncertainty early in its development because the linear programming world was uncharted territory for the team members.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] The limitations of linear programming, which seemed to be a central part of how the product would likely function, were not well understood.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] To address the team’s consternation over this insufficiently understood dependency, we opted to initially build a simplified solver engine (the so-called "Stupid Solver") that applied some simple heuristics as to how services should be arranged based upon the user’s specified requirements.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] While the Stupid Solver would never yield a truly optimal solution, it gave the team a sense that our vision for Auxon was achievable even if we didn’t build something perfect from day one.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] When deploying approximation to help speed development, it’s important to undertake the work in a way that allows the team to make future enhancements and revisit approximation.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] In the case of the Stupid Solver, the entire solver interface was abstracted away within Auxon such that the solver internals could be swapped out at a later date.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Eventually, as we built confidence in a unified linear programming model, it was a simple operation to switch out the Stupid Solver for something, well, smarter.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Auxon’s product requirements also had some unknowns.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Building software with fuzzy requirements can be a frustrating challenge, but some degree of uncertainty need not be a showstopper.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Use this fuzziness as an incentive to ensure that the software is designed to be both general and modular.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] For instance, one of the aims of the Auxon project was to integrate with automation systems within Google to allow an Allocation Plan to be directly enacted on production (assigning resources and turning up/turning down/resizing services as appropriate).
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] However, at the time, the world of automation systems was in a great deal of flux, as a huge variety of approaches were in use.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Rather than try to design unique solutions to allow Auxon to work with each individual tool, we instead shaped the Allocation Plan to be universally useful such that these automation systems could work on their own integration points.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] This "agnostic" approach became key to Auxon’s process for onboarding new customers, because it allowed customers to begin using Auxon without switching to a particular turnup automation tool, forecasting tool, or performance data tool.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] We also leveraged modular designs to deal with fuzzy requirements when building a model of machine performance within Auxon.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Data on future machine platform performance (e.g., CPU) was scarce, but our users wanted a way to model various scenarios of machine power.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] We abstracted away the machine data behind a single interface, allowing the user to swap in different models of future machine performance.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] We later extended this modularity further, based on increasingly defined requirements, to provide a simple machine performance modeling library that worked within this interface.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] If there’s one theme to draw from our Auxon case study, it’s that the old motto of "launch and iterate" is particularly relevant in SRE software development projects.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Don’t wait for the perfect design; rather, keep the overall vision in mind while moving ahead with design and development.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] When you encounter areas of uncertainty, design the software to be flexible enough so that if process or strategy changes at a higher level, you don’t incur a huge rework cost.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] But at the same time, stay grounded by making sure that general solutions have a real-world–specific implementation that demonstrates the utility of the design.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] As with any product, SRE-developed software must be designed with knowledge of its users and requirements.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] It needs to drive adoption through utility, performance, and demonstrated ability to both benefit Google’s production reliability goals and to better the lives of SREs.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] The process of socializing a product and achieving buy-in across an organization is key to the project’s success.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Don’t underestimate the effort required to raise awareness and interest in your software product—a single presentation or email announcement isn’t enough.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] It’s important to consider the perspective of the customer in making your product usable.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] An engineer might not have the time or the inclination to dig into the source code to figure out how to use a tool.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Although internal customers are generally more tolerant of rough edges and early alphas than external customers, it’s still necessary to provide documentation.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] SREs are busy, and if your solution is too difficult or confusing, they will write their own solution.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] When an engineer with years of familiarity in a problem space begins designing a product, it’s easy to imagine a utopian end-state for the work.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] However, it’s important to differentiate aspirational goals of the product from minimum success criteria (or Minimum Viable Product).
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Projects can lose credibility and fail by promising too much, too soon; at the same time, if a product doesn’t promise a sufficiently rewarding outcome, it can be difficult to overcome the necessary activation energy to convince internal teams to try something new.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Demonstrating steady, incremental progress via small releases raises user confidence in your team’s ability to deliver useful software.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] In the case of Auxon, we struck a balance by planning a long-term roadmap alongside short-term fixes.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] The team developing Auxon realized that a one-size solution might not fit all; many larger teams already had home-grown solutions for capacity planning that worked passably well.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] While their custom tools weren’t perfect, these teams didn’t experience sufficient pain in the capacity planning process to try a new tool, especially an alpha release with rough edges.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] The initial versions of Auxon intentionally targeted teams that had no existing capacity planning processes in place.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Because these teams would have to invest configuration effort whether they adopted an existing tool or our new approach, they were interested in adopting the newest tool.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] The early successes Auxon achieved with these teams demonstrated the utility of the project, and turned the customers themselves into advocates for the tool.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Quantifying the usefulness of the product proved further beneficial; when we onboarded one of Google’s Business Areas, the team authored a case study detailing the process and comparing the before and after results.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] The time savings and reduction of human toil alone presented a huge incentive for other teams to give Auxon a try.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Even though software developed within SRE targets an audience of TPMs and engineers with high technical proficiency, any sufficiently innovative software still presents a learning curve to new users.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Don’t be afraid to provide white glove customer support for early adopters to help them through the onboarding process.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Sometimes automation also entails a host of emotional concerns, such as fear that someone’s job will be replaced by a shell script.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] By working one-on-one with early users, you can address those fears personally, and demonstrate that rather than owning the toil of performing a tedious task manually, the team instead owns the configurations, processes, and ultimate results of their technical work.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Later adopters are convinced by the happy examples of early adopters.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Furthermore, because Google’s SRE teams are distributed across the globe, early-adopter advocates for a project are particularly beneficial, because they can serve as local experts for other teams interested in trying out the project.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] An idea that we’ve termed *agnosticism*—writing the software to be generalized to allow myriad data sources as input—was a key principle of Auxon’s design.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Agnosticism meant that customers weren’t required to commit to any one tool in order to use the Auxon framework.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] This approach allowed Auxon to remain of sufficient general utility even as teams with divergent use cases began to use it.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] We approached potential users with the message, "come as you are; we’ll work with what you’ve got." By avoiding over-customizing for one or two big users, we achieved broader adoption across the organization and lowered the barrier to entry for new services.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] We’ve also consciously endeavored to avoid the pitfall of defining success as 100% adoption across the organization.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] In many cases, there are diminishing returns on closing the last mile to enable a feature set that is sufficient for every service in the long tail at Google.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] In selecting engineers to work on an SRE software development product, we’ve found great benefit from creating a seed team that combines generalists who are able to get up to speed quickly on a new topic with engineers possessing a breadth of knowledge and experience.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] A diversity of experiences covers blind spots as well as the pitfalls of assuming that every team’s use case is the same as yours.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] It’s essential for your team to establish a working relationship with necessary specialists, and for your engineers to be comfortable working in a new problem space.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] For SRE teams at most companies, venturing into this new problem space requires outsourcing tasks or working with consultants, but SRE teams at larger organizations may be able to partner with in-house experts.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] As project development continued and Auxon’s feature set grew more broad and complex, the team acquired members with backgrounds in statistics and mathematical optimization, which at a smaller company might be akin to bringing an outside consultant in-house.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] These new team members were able to identify areas for improvement when the project’s basic functionality was complete and adding finesse had become our top priority.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] The right time to engage specialists will, of course, vary from project to project.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] As a rough guideline, the project should be successfully off the ground and demonstrably successful, such that the skills of the current team would be significantly bolstered by the additional expertise.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] What makes a project a good candidate to take the leap from one-off tool to fully fledged software engineering effort?
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Strong positive signals include engineers with firsthand experience in the relative domain who are interested in working on the project, and a target user base that is highly technical (and therefore able to provide high-signal bug reports during the early phases of development).
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] The project should provide noticeable benefits, such as reducing toil for SREs, improving an existing piece of infrastructure, or streamlining a complex process.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] It’s important for the project to fit into the overall set of objectives for the organization, so that engineering leaders can weigh its potential impact and subsequently advocate for your project, both with their reporting teams and with other teams that might interface with their teams.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Cross-organizational socialization and review help prevent disjoint or overlapping efforts, and a product that can easily be established as furthering a department-wide objective is easier to staff and support.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Many of the same red flags you might instinctively identify in any software project, such as software that touches many moving parts at once, or software design that requires an all-or-nothing approach that prevents iterative development.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Because Google SRE teams are currently organized around the services they run, SRE-developed projects are particularly at risk of being overly specific work that only benefits a small percentage of the organization.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Because team incentives are aligned primarily to provide a great experience for the users of one particular service, projects often fail to generalize to a broader use case as standardization across SRE teams comes in second place.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] At the opposite end of the spectrum, overly generic frameworks can be equally problematic; if a tool strives to be too flexible and too universal, it runs the risk of not quite fitting any use case, and therefore having insufficient value in and of itself.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Projects with grand scope and abstract goals often require significant development effort, but lack the concrete use cases required to deliver end-user benefit on a reasonable time frame.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] As an example of a broad use case: a layer-3 load balancer developed by Google SREs proved so successful over the years that it was repurposed as a customer-facing product offering via Google Cloud Load Balancer [Eis16].
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] SREs are often generalists, as the desire to learn breadth-first instead of depth-first lends itself well to understanding the bigger picture (and there are few pictures bigger than the intricate inner workings of modern technical infrastructure).
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] These engineers often have strong coding and software development skills, but may not have the traditional SWE experience of being part of a product team or having to think about customer feature requests.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Dedicated, noninterrupted, project work time is essential to any software development effort.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Dedicated project time is necessary to enable progress on a project, because it’s nearly impossible to write code—much less to concentrate on larger, more impactful projects—when you’re thrashing between several tasks in the course of an hour.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Therefore, the ability to work on a software project without interrupts is often an attractive reason for engineers to begin working on a development project.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Such time must be aggressively defended.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] The majority of software products developed within SRE begin as side projects whose utility leads them to grow and become formalized.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] However, in any of these scenarios—and this is a point worth stressing—it’s essential that the SREs involved in any development effort continue working as SREs instead of becoming full-time developers embedded in the SRE organization.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Immersion in the world of production gives SREs performing development work an invaluable perspective, as they are both the creator and the customer for any product.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] If you like the idea of organized software development in SRE, you’re probably wondering how to introduce a software development model to an SRE organization focused on production support.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] First, recognize that this goal is as much an organizational change as it is a technical challenge.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] SREs are used to working closely with their teammates, quickly analyzing and reacting to problems.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Therefore, you’re working against the natural instinct of an SRE to quickly write some code to meet their immediate needs.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] If your SRE team is small, this approach may not be problematic.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] However, as your organization grows, this ad hoc approach won’t scale, instead resulting in largely functional, yet narrow or single-purpose, software solutions that can’t be shared, which inevitably lead to duplicated efforts and wasted time.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Next, think about what you want to achieve by developing software in SRE.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Do you just want to foster better software development practices within your team, or are you interested in software development that produces results that can be used across teams, possibly as a standard for the organization?
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] In larger established organizations, the latter change will take time, possibly spanning multiple years.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Such a change needs to be tackled on multiple fronts, but has a higher payback.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] It’s important to define and communicate your strategy, plans, and—most importantly—the benefits SRE gains from this effort.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] the strategy should be pursued, you know you’ve passed the first hurdle.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] SREs have many skills, but it’s relatively common for an SRE to lack experience as part of a team that built and shipped a product to a set of users.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] In order to develop useful software, you’re effectively creating a product team.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] That team includes required roles and skills that your SRE organization may not have formerly demanded.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Will someone play the role of product manager, acting as the customer advocate?
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Does your tech lead or project manager have the skills and/or experience to run an agile development process?
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Begin filling these gaps by taking advantage of the skills already present in your company.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Ask your product development team to help you establish agile practices via training or coaching.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Solicit consulting time from a product manager to help you define product requirements and prioritize feature work.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Given a large enough software-development opportunity, there may be a case to hire dedicated people for these roles.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Making the case to hire for these roles is easier once you have some positive experiment results.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] As you initiate an SRE software development program, your efforts will be followed by many watchful eyes.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] It’s important to establish credibility by delivering some product of value in a reasonable amount of time.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Your first round of products should aim for relatively straightforward and achievable targets—ones without controversy or existing solutions.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] We also found success in pairing this approach with a six-month rhythm of product update releases that provided additional useful features.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] This release cycle allowed teams to focus on identifying the right set of features to build, and then building those features while simultaneously learning how to be a productive software development team.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] After the initial launch, some Google teams moved to a push-on-green model for even faster delivery and feedback.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] As you start to develop software, you may be tempted to cut corners.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Resist this urge by holding yourself to the same standards to which your product development teams are held.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] It takes a long time to build credibility for your software development efforts, but only a short time to lose credibility due to a misstep.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Software engineering projects within Google SRE have flourished as the organization has grown, and in many cases the lessons learned from and successful execution of earlier software development projects have paved the way for subsequent endeavors.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] The unique hands-on production experience that SREs bring to developing tools can lead to innovative approaches to age-old problems, as seen with the development of Auxon to address the complex problem of capacity planning.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] SRE-driven software projects are also noticeably beneficial to the company in developing a sustainable model for supporting services at scale.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Because SREs often develop software to streamline inefficient processes or automate common tasks, these projects mean that the SRE team doesn’t have to scale linearly with the size of the services they support.
[src:capacity-planning/software-engineering-in-sre] Ultimately, the benefits of having SREs devoting some of their time to software development are reaped by the company, the SRE organization, and the SREs themselves.
